WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.370 --> 00:00:05.770
Prof: What is a Gospel
and how should we read it?

00:00:05.770 --> 00:00:10.189
Popular opinion may think that
the Gospels are biographies of

00:00:10.189 --> 00:00:13.651
Jesus, but they're not
biographies, at least not

00:00:13.651 --> 00:00:16.230
anything like the modern sense.
 

00:00:16.230 --> 00:00:20.917
We don't get much of a personal
portrait of Jesus from the

00:00:20.917 --> 00:00:21.740
Gospels.
 

00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:24.131
We don't know anything about
how he developed,

00:00:24.131 --> 00:00:27.054
how he went from being an
obnoxious teenager to being an

00:00:27.054 --> 00:00:28.330
apocalyptic prophet.
 

00:00:28.330 --> 00:00:31.840
We don't know about his
relationship to his parents,

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:35.354
his brothers and sisters,
we don't know all kinds of

00:00:35.354 --> 00:00:39.557
things that a modern biography
would automatically be expected

00:00:39.557 --> 00:00:40.660
to tell you.
 

00:00:40.660 --> 00:00:43.960
The Gospels aren't biographies.
 

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:46.884
Somebody once said,
a scholar once called Mark,

00:00:46.884 --> 00:00:50.190
a passion narrative with an
extended introduction.

00:00:50.190 --> 00:00:52.250
What's a passion narrative?
 

00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:55.634
Passion comes from the Latin
passio which doesn't mean

00:00:55.634 --> 00:00:57.449
just desire,
it could mean that in the

00:00:57.449 --> 00:00:58.741
ancient world,
but it also means

00:00:58.741 --> 00:00:59.650
"suffering."
 

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:03.497
"Suffering"
is what passio means and

00:01:03.497 --> 00:01:08.010
so it's the suffering of Jesus
that happens at his arrest,

00:01:08.010 --> 00:01:11.328
his trial, his crucifixion,
and then the resurrection.

00:01:11.328 --> 00:01:14.316
All of that's part of what
scholars call the passion

00:01:14.316 --> 00:01:15.019
narrative.
 

00:01:15.019 --> 00:01:18.885
If you notice,
that occupies a huge part of

00:01:18.885 --> 00:01:20.819
the Gospel of Mark.
 

00:01:20.819 --> 00:01:23.370
The Gospel of Mark is our
shortest Gospel that's in the

00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:23.750
canon.
 

00:01:23.750 --> 00:01:26.367
It's only sixteen chapters,
of course the chapters and

00:01:26.367 --> 00:01:29.084
verse numbers weren't there in
the original manuscripts,

00:01:29.084 --> 00:01:30.269
it was just written.
 

00:01:30.269 --> 00:01:31.768
In fact, they didn't even
divide up words,

00:01:31.768 --> 00:01:33.230
and they have very little
punctuation.

00:01:33.230 --> 00:01:35.486
It was just one capital letter
after another,

00:01:35.486 --> 00:01:38.513
which is one of the reasons
that ancient tended to read text

00:01:38.513 --> 00:01:39.180
out loud.
 

00:01:39.180 --> 00:01:41.310
They didn't read silently to
themselves.

00:01:41.310 --> 00:01:43.638
One of the reasons is because
it's easier to read a text that

00:01:43.638 --> 00:01:46.162
had no word divisions,
it was all capital letters,

00:01:46.162 --> 00:01:48.328
no punctuation,
it wasn't divided up into

00:01:48.328 --> 00:01:50.229
sentences,
it was much easier to read that

00:01:50.229 --> 00:01:51.860
if you read it out loud to
yourself,

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:53.300
so that's the way ancient
people read.

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:56.681
We don't have chapter numbers
and verse divisions,

00:01:56.681 --> 00:02:00.683
those are all later creations
that came about in the Middle

00:02:00.683 --> 00:02:02.409
Ages in Christianity.
 

00:02:02.409 --> 00:02:05.938
By modern reckoning,
therefore, there are sixteen

00:02:05.938 --> 00:02:09.602
chapters in Mark,
that's the shortest Gospel,

00:02:09.602 --> 00:02:12.573
and of that,
one-third of Mark is just the

00:02:12.573 --> 00:02:15.957
last week of Jesus' life,
the passion narrative part of

00:02:15.957 --> 00:02:16.188
it.
 

00:02:16.188 --> 00:02:18.615
As this scholar said,
Mark is really a passion

00:02:18.615 --> 00:02:20.878
narrative with an extended
introduction.

00:02:20.878 --> 00:02:23.098
Notice what you get if you have
an outline of Mark.

00:02:23.098 --> 00:02:25.712
Chapter 1, verse 1 is the
title, "the

00:02:25.712 --> 00:02:29.090
euangelion,"
or "the gospel according

00:02:29.090 --> 00:02:31.639
to Jesus Christ,"
and it doesn't say

00:02:31.639 --> 00:02:35.400
"according to Mark"
in the title because that name

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:36.930
was added later.
 

00:02:36.930 --> 00:02:38.240
That's the title of the book.
 

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:41.697
Then for the next few verses
from 1:2, that is Chapter 1,

00:02:41.697 --> 00:02:44.846
verse 2 to verse 13,
you get an initial introduction

00:02:44.846 --> 00:02:47.440
to Jesus, just a little bit
about him.

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:53.173
Then from 1:14 to 9:50,
so nine chapters is Jesus'

00:02:53.173 --> 00:02:56.323
Galilean ministry,
his healings,

00:02:56.323 --> 00:02:58.348
his teachings,
his traveling around,

00:02:58.348 --> 00:03:01.411
his miracles that all take
place in Galilee which is where

00:03:01.411 --> 00:03:02.110
he is from.
 

00:03:02.110 --> 00:03:04.866
That's of course the northern
part of Palestine,

00:03:04.866 --> 00:03:08.330
whereas, Judea is down in the
southern part of Palestine.

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:13.033
Then Chapters 11 through 15 are
all just the last week in

00:03:13.033 --> 00:03:16.983
Jerusalem, again,
five chapters just on his last

00:03:16.983 --> 00:03:17.740
week.
 

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:24.270
Then Chapter 16:1-8 is rumors
of the resurrection.

00:03:24.270 --> 00:03:26.520
Why do I say rumors of the
resurrection?

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:29.098
Because if you'll notice in the
Gospel of Mark,

00:03:29.098 --> 00:03:32.305
if Mark ends at Chapter 16:8,
and there has been some

00:03:32.305 --> 00:03:36.250
controversy about whether it
really is supposed to end there,

00:03:36.250 --> 00:03:39.120
but in most of your modern
editions it ends at 16:8.

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:41.418
If that's true,
you don't actually see the

00:03:41.418 --> 00:03:42.538
resurrected Jesus.
 

00:03:42.538 --> 00:03:45.750
You just get--he doesn't appear
on the stage so to speak.

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:48.491
You only get reports that he
has been raised,

00:03:48.491 --> 00:03:50.550
or one report that he's raised.
 

00:03:50.550 --> 00:03:53.598
Then the women are told by this
young man,

00:03:53.598 --> 00:03:56.803
who's sitting at the tomb,
probably supposed to represent

00:03:56.803 --> 00:03:58.550
an angel,
to go and tell the other

00:03:58.550 --> 00:04:01.378
disciples that he's raised and
he'll go before them to Galilee.

00:04:01.378 --> 00:04:03.610
Notice the women don't tell
them, it says that the women

00:04:03.610 --> 00:04:04.908
were afraid and they ran away.
 

00:04:04.908 --> 00:04:08.574
You don't even get many reports
about Jesus' resurrection in

00:04:08.574 --> 00:04:10.394
Mark;
you just get the one young man

00:04:10.394 --> 00:04:12.840
at the tomb telling the women
that he's been raised.

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:16.694
A huge bulk of the book tells
us about the last week of Jesus'

00:04:16.694 --> 00:04:19.120
life,
and even in the previous ten

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:23.194
chapters of the book,
you have Jesus talking about

00:04:23.194 --> 00:04:25.509
his upcoming crucifixion.
 

00:04:25.509 --> 00:04:27.927
These passion predictions,
we call them,

00:04:27.927 --> 00:04:31.214
that occur in the Gospel,
you have several of those in

00:04:31.214 --> 00:04:32.639
the Gospel of Mark.
 

00:04:32.639 --> 00:04:35.550
There are several references to
Jesus' upcoming death.

00:04:35.550 --> 00:04:38.714
That focuses our attention even
more on the last part of the

00:04:38.714 --> 00:04:39.089
book.
 

00:04:39.089 --> 00:04:40.740
Is that important?
 

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:44.595
Does that tell us anything
about what sort of thing Mark's

00:04:44.595 --> 00:04:47.029
Gospel is if it's not a
biography?

00:04:47.029 --> 00:04:49.740
Let's look at the ending also.
 

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:53.788
Mark 16, now remember,
I want you to bring your Bibles

00:04:53.788 --> 00:04:54.629
to class.
 

00:04:54.629 --> 00:04:57.990
Why do I want you to bring your
Bibles to class?

00:04:57.990 --> 00:04:59.949
Yes?
 

00:04:59.949 --> 00:05:00.120
Student:  Because you're
going to lie.

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:02.930
Prof: Because I will lie
to you.

00:05:02.930 --> 00:05:05.899
I may something that's not true
and you need to check me out,

00:05:05.899 --> 00:05:07.778
de omnibus
dubitandum.

00:05:07.778 --> 00:05:09.735
When the sabbath was over [Mark
16]

00:05:09.735 --> 00:05:12.266
Mary Magdalene,
and Mary the mother of James,

00:05:12.266 --> 00:05:15.543
and Salome brought spices,
so that they might go an anoint

00:05:15.543 --> 00:05:16.120
him.
 

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:18.894
And very early on the first day
of the week, when the sun had

00:05:18.894 --> 00:05:20.329
risen, they went to the tomb.
 

00:05:20.329 --> 00:05:22.242
They had been saying to one
another, "Who will roll

00:05:22.242 --> 00:05:24.329
away the stone for us from the
entrance to the tomb?"

00:05:24.329 --> 00:05:25.990
When they looked up,
they say that the stone,

00:05:25.990 --> 00:05:27.990
which was very large,
had already been rolled back.

00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:30.646
As they entered the tomb,
they saw a young man,

00:05:30.646 --> 00:05:33.709
dressed in a white robe,
sitting on the right side;

00:05:33.709 --> 00:05:34.940
and they were alarmed.
 

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:36.949
But he said to them,
"Do not be alarmed;

00:05:36.949 --> 00:05:39.259
you are looking for Jesus of
Nazareth, who was crucified.

00:05:39.259 --> 00:05:40.740
He has been raised;
he is not here.

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:42.879
Look, there is the place they
laid him.

00:05:42.879 --> 00:05:46.641
But go, tell his disciples and
Peter that he is going ahead of

00:05:46.641 --> 00:05:48.908
you to Galilee;
there you will see him,

00:05:48.908 --> 00:05:50.339
just as he told you."
 

00:05:50.339 --> 00:05:53.158
So they went out and fled from
the tomb, for terror and

00:05:53.158 --> 00:05:56.560
amazement had seized them;
and they said nothing to anyone

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:57.940
for they were afraid.
 

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:01.021
Now you'll notice there's--and
maybe some of your Bible's there

00:06:01.021 --> 00:06:03.060
will be a paragraph under that
titled,

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:05.649
"A Shorter Ending of
Mark."

00:06:05.649 --> 00:06:07.961
All that had been commanded of
them they briefly told to those

00:06:07.961 --> 00:06:08.528
around Peter.
 

00:06:08.528 --> 00:06:10.562
And afterwards Jesus himself
sent out through them,

00:06:10.562 --> 00:06:12.394
from east to west,
the sacred and imperishable

00:06:12.394 --> 00:06:13.939
proclamation of eternal
salvation.

00:06:13.939 --> 00:06:17.000
Then you'll notice there's
maybe a few paragraphs,

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.185
called by your editors,
"The Longer Ending of

00:06:19.185 --> 00:06:20.970
Mark," and it has several
verses.

00:06:20.970 --> 00:06:22.500
I'm not going to bother to read
that to you,

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:25.278
but if you look at that,
the little incidents--

00:06:25.278 --> 00:06:28.182
several of the incidents in
that longer ending of Mark could

00:06:28.182 --> 00:06:30.889
sound familiar to you if you
know the other Gospels,

00:06:30.889 --> 00:06:32.240
how they end.
 

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:36.774
What scholars now believe is
that probably the Gospel of Mark

00:06:36.774 --> 00:06:39.269
really did end at Chapter 16:8.
 

00:06:39.269 --> 00:06:41.605
Some people said,
well that's no way end a book,

00:06:41.605 --> 00:06:44.538
the women don't tell anything,
it just says they were afraid

00:06:44.538 --> 00:06:46.180
and they ran away,
that's it.

00:06:46.180 --> 00:06:49.728
Even the Greek that it ends in
is a very short little sentence

00:06:49.728 --> 00:06:52.230
that's an odd way to end a book
in Greek.

00:06:52.230 --> 00:06:55.817
Some people--scholars have said
well maybe that wasn't

00:06:55.817 --> 00:06:58.711
originally the ending,
maybe Mark was writing along

00:06:58.711 --> 00:07:01.329
and he got to 16 and he fell
over an died of a heart attack.

00:07:01.329 --> 00:07:05.497
Or maybe he left the manuscript
out and some mice ate the end of

00:07:05.497 --> 00:07:09.137
it, because you roll up the
scroll and you just have the

00:07:09.137 --> 00:07:11.189
leftover parts at the back.
 

00:07:11.189 --> 00:07:14.490
Or maybe it got in a fire and
burnt, maybe the last few

00:07:14.490 --> 00:07:17.180
verses--the last part of the
Gospel burnt.

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:20.375
Obviously ancient people had
the same sense of uneasiness

00:07:20.375 --> 00:07:22.627
with the way--
with Mark ending at 16:8 and

00:07:22.627 --> 00:07:25.446
what you've got in that shorter
ending and the longer ending

00:07:25.446 --> 00:07:27.310
were later compositions of
scribes,

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:29.377
Christian scribes,
who thought you can't end

00:07:29.377 --> 00:07:31.925
Mark's Gospel that way,
so they made up those other

00:07:31.925 --> 00:07:34.901
verses and they put them at the
end of the manuscript they were

00:07:34.901 --> 00:07:35.430
copying.
 

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:38.728
Because you remember before
printing presses all manuscripts

00:07:38.728 --> 00:07:42.129
had to be made one by one,
by somebody sitting down with a

00:07:42.129 --> 00:07:44.449
quill,
and ink, and a papyrus and just

00:07:44.449 --> 00:07:47.858
copying it word by word,
so other scribes when copying

00:07:47.858 --> 00:07:50.089
this over must have added that
on.

00:07:50.089 --> 00:07:52.509
In fact that looks very much
like the longer ending,

00:07:52.509 --> 00:07:56.519
it was scribes who knew some
events from the Gospels,

00:07:56.519 --> 00:07:58.740
and they took some events from
Matthew,

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:00.899
Luke, and John,
and they stuck them into a

00:08:00.899 --> 00:08:04.185
little paragraph and they said,
well that must be the way Mark

00:08:04.185 --> 00:08:05.930
really intended to end his
Gospel.

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:08.776
In the twentieth century,
basically, modern scholars have

00:08:08.776 --> 00:08:11.420
come to pretty much reject most
of those theories.

00:08:11.420 --> 00:08:15.644
At least we take the Gospel of
Mark as ending at 16:8,

00:08:15.644 --> 00:08:17.319
even intentionally.
 

00:08:17.319 --> 00:08:21.605
But if you do that then you
still have to explain why end a

00:08:21.605 --> 00:08:24.672
Gospel this way,
it's not a normal way to end a

00:08:24.672 --> 00:08:26.271
book,
and it's not the way the other

00:08:26.271 --> 00:08:27.079
Gospels end at all.
 

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:31.259
The very ending of Mark is one
of the problems of the text that

00:08:31.259 --> 00:08:34.090
scholars feel like we have to
deal with.

00:08:34.090 --> 00:08:38.260
This all demonstrates though
that scholars don't read the

00:08:38.260 --> 00:08:42.730
Gospels as biographies or as
even straightforward accounts of

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:43.548
events.
 

00:08:43.548 --> 00:08:46.765
Last time I tried to show you
how you can't take the Book of

00:08:46.765 --> 00:08:49.546
Acts and Paul's letters as
simply being a historical

00:08:49.546 --> 00:08:52.888
description of what happened,
because each of these documents

00:08:52.888 --> 00:08:54.207
had agendas,
these authors had

00:08:54.207 --> 00:08:55.808
things--points they wanted to
get across.

00:08:55.808 --> 00:09:00.836
We learn to read these Gospels
in twentieth century by using

00:09:00.836 --> 00:09:03.990
the method of historical
criticism.

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:07.174
The criticism part of that
doesn't mean necessarily being

00:09:07.174 --> 00:09:09.726
critical of it,
that is criticizing the text,

00:09:09.726 --> 00:09:12.149
it just means reading it with
critical eyes,

00:09:12.149 --> 00:09:14.590
with questioning eyes,
with, if you were,

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:16.100
doubting eyes in some cases.
 

00:09:16.100 --> 00:09:18.457
What we do is we read these
texts not for what they tell us

00:09:18.457 --> 00:09:21.154
about the events in the past,
although you can read this,

00:09:21.154 --> 00:09:24.049
but we actually read the text
as if they were intentional

00:09:24.049 --> 00:09:27.254
documents written by authors who
had points they wanted to make

00:09:27.254 --> 00:09:30.511
and they tell the story the way
they tell the story because they

00:09:30.511 --> 00:09:31.649
have a message.
 

00:09:31.649 --> 00:09:34.434
The important thing is not what
really happened or what lies

00:09:34.434 --> 00:09:37.080
behind the text for modern
scholars most of the time,

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:38.990
unless you're doing historical
Jesus research,

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:42.009
and I'll lecture about that at
one period later.

00:09:42.009 --> 00:09:44.971
But most of the time we're
saying, what did Mark as an

00:09:44.971 --> 00:09:46.090
author want to do?
 

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:48.533
Therefore we say,
why would end the Gospel this

00:09:48.533 --> 00:09:49.649
way if he did that?
 

00:09:49.649 --> 00:09:52.470
Now that's--notice this
historical critical method,

00:09:52.470 --> 00:09:53.950
which is what I'm teaching in
this class,

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:56.460
is somewhat different from
several other ways of reading

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:56.779
text.
 

00:09:56.779 --> 00:09:59.697
I'm not implying by this that
historical critical method is

00:09:59.697 --> 00:10:02.767
the correct method or will give
you the correct meaning of the

00:10:02.767 --> 00:10:03.220
text.
 

00:10:03.220 --> 00:10:06.400
I believe that it's perfectly
legitimate for Christians,

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:08.600
for example,
to read these texts to get

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:11.840
something religious out of the
text for their lives.

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:13.678
For personal guidance,
for doctrine,

00:10:13.678 --> 00:10:16.254
for images of Jesus,
to help their relationship to

00:10:16.254 --> 00:10:17.200
God, whatever.
 

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:19.530
That's a perfectly legitimate
way, in my view,

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:21.759
to read a text,
to read it theologically.

00:10:21.759 --> 00:10:24.543
But a theological reading of
the text is not the same thing

00:10:24.543 --> 00:10:26.798
as a historical critical reading
of the text.

00:10:26.798 --> 00:10:29.354
The historian is what I'm
playing my role here in this

00:10:29.354 --> 00:10:29.740
class.
 

00:10:29.740 --> 00:10:32.798
I don't care whether these
texts have anything theological

00:10:32.798 --> 00:10:34.730
to say to you or to me
personally.

00:10:34.730 --> 00:10:38.018
What I care about is what kind
of theological message was this

00:10:38.018 --> 00:10:40.822
original writer intending to
give, and to whom was he

00:10:40.822 --> 00:10:42.168
intending to give it?
 

00:10:42.168 --> 00:10:45.020
The theological way to reading
is one way, perfectly fine way,

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:47.779
but it's not the historical
critical reading necessarily.

00:10:47.779 --> 00:10:51.216
There are also literary ways of
reading these texts and this has

00:10:51.216 --> 00:10:54.326
been a very common thing in
English departments for people

00:10:54.326 --> 00:10:56.889
to write an account of the
Gospel of Mark,

00:10:56.889 --> 00:11:00.677
it's been a particularly
significant Gospel for modern

00:11:00.677 --> 00:11:05.110
literary people to retell or
talk about the Gospel of Mark,

00:11:05.110 --> 00:11:06.668
do a literary reading of it.
 

00:11:06.668 --> 00:11:09.335
There they're looking for
things like the plot of it,

00:11:09.335 --> 00:11:11.178
the way it accomplishes its
story.

00:11:11.178 --> 00:11:14.248
Are there figures and
