00:11:44.269 --> 00:11:47.107
Lots of different ways to read
these texts and I'm going to

00:11:47.107 --> 00:11:49.163
teach you this historical
critical reading,

00:11:49.163 --> 00:11:50.678
which means certain things.
 

00:11:50.678 --> 00:11:53.535
It means we're not going to
read the Gospel of Mark through

00:11:53.535 --> 00:11:55.308
the lens of Matthew,
Luke or John.

00:11:55.308 --> 00:11:58.600
We're going to take Mark's own
Gospel as standing on its own.

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:00.975
So we're not going to rush off
to another Gospel,

00:12:00.975 --> 00:12:03.302
or to Acts, or the letters of
Paul to provide an

00:12:03.302 --> 00:12:05.528
interpretative clue for how to
read Mark.

00:12:05.528 --> 00:12:08.649
We're going to read Mark as
Mark by itself,

00:12:08.649 --> 00:12:11.226
and that's one of the
fundamental rules of historical

00:12:11.226 --> 00:12:14.200
criticism is don't harmonize
different texts in the Bible.

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:15.840
Take them each individually.
 

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:19.428
Another one is you have to
avoid anachronism that is you

00:12:19.428 --> 00:12:23.476
can't attribute a meaning to the
text of Mark that doesn't make

00:12:23.476 --> 00:12:26.740
sense in the first century in
his own context.

00:12:26.740 --> 00:12:28.399
For example,
if you're a Christian,

00:12:28.399 --> 00:12:31.232
you're going to read some of
the Psalms in the Hebrew Bible

00:12:31.232 --> 00:12:33.918
