probably, most Christians do.

00:12:33.918 --> 00:12:36.971
When the Psalmist says,
"The Lord said to my Lord,

00:12:36.971 --> 00:12:39.969
Sit at my right hand and I will
make your enemies your

00:12:39.969 --> 00:12:41.100
footstool."
 

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:45.023
Christians have traditionally
said the first "Lord"

00:12:45.023 --> 00:12:47.131
there is God,
and the second "Lord"

00:12:47.131 --> 00:12:49.431
is Jesus,
and this is an Old Testament

00:12:49.431 --> 00:12:52.519
reference to God the Father and
God the Son.

00:12:52.519 --> 00:12:56.542
This is a christological Psalm,
that's a theological way of

00:12:56.542 --> 00:12:57.928
reading the Psalm.
 

00:12:57.928 --> 00:13:00.751
It doesn't pass the test of
historical criticism because

00:13:00.751 --> 00:13:03.421
historians will point out,
look the original Psalmist

00:13:03.421 --> 00:13:05.320
didn't know anything about
Jesus.

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:07.740
He wasn't prophesying about
Jesus personally,

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:10.240
he was talking probably to the
David the King,

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:13.940
the Psalms meant to talk to
David, or to David's descendants

00:13:13.940 --> 00:13:16.009
who sit on the throne of Judah.
 

00:13:16.009 --> 00:13:20.850
Anachronism has to be avoided
in historical critical readings.

00:13:20.850 --> 00:13:23.083
